[13]\~ \~  The phrase 'subject to' has no a priori meaning (see Pangbourne Properties Ltd v Gill & Ramsden (Pty) Ltd 1996 (1) SA 1182 (A) at 1187J - 1188A). While the phrase is often used in statutory contexts to establish what is dominant and what is subservient, its meaning in a statutory context is not confined thereto and it frequently means no more than that a qualification or limitation is introduced so that it can be read as meaning 'except as curtailed by' (see Premier, Eastern Cape, and Another v Sekeleni 2003 (4) SA 369 (SCA) at para 14). And Megarry J stated in C & J Clark Ltd v Inland Revenue Commissioners [1973] 2 All ER 513 at 520: }
